B) pKa for each tautomeric form (microscopic pKa)
Dominant ionizable group is the 4‑hydroxy (phenolic) OH on the coumarin ring. The side chain and lactone/carbonyls are not appreciably basic under physiological conditions.

Interim predicted pKa (to be replaced by Rowan):
- T1 (4-hydroxy): pKa ≈ 4.9 ± 0.3
- T2 (4-keto): no labile phenolic proton; relevant micro‑pKa corresponds to the enolization back to T1; effective acidity is governed by T1’s phenolic site. For practical speciation at biochemical pH, T1 controls the acid-base behavior.

C) Dominant form at pH 7.4
Using Henderson–Hasselbalch for T1 (phenolic acid):
- Fraction deprotonated (A−) = 1 / (1 + 10^(pKa − pH))

- A− fraction ≈ 1 / (1 + 0.00316) ≈ 0.9968 → 99.68%
Therefore, at pH 7.4 the dominant microstate is the anionic form of the 4‑hydroxy tautomer (T1−). T2 contributes negligibly.
